solutions.content:
This solution is based on a circular list approach, where we "connect" the end to the beginning. Knowing dimensions of a matrix, we can work with it as a 1-dimensional array, where iterating all elements looks like `rowIndex * rowSize + columnIndex`. This also means that given an element index `i`, we can find row and column indices - `rowIndex = i / rowSize` (as an integer), `columnIndex = i mod rowSize`.

```
/**
 * @param {number[][]} grid
 * @param {number} k
 * @return {number[][]}
 */
var shiftGrid = function(grid, k) {
  const xSize = grid[0].length;
  const elements = xSize * grid.length;

  // no need to shift if it's a full loop
  if (k === elements) {
    return grid;
  }

  const offset = k % elements;

  // use modulo arithmetic to map 1-dim array index to matrix row and column position (2-dim array)
  // X is a column index, Y is a row index
  const coord = (idx) => [
    idx % xSize, // X
    Math.floor(idx / xSize), // Y
  ];

  const overflow = Array(offset);
  for (let i = elements - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    // matrix coordinates of where an element is going to be moved
    const [newX, newY] = coord(i);

    // save the last "offset" elements to be prepended later
    if (i >= elements - offset) {
      overflow[elements - i - 1] = grid[newY][newX];
    }    

    // get the saved elements and write them to the beginning
    if (i < offset) {
      grid[newY][newX] = overflow[offset - i - 1];
      continue;
    }

    // move the rest by offset positions
    const [oldX, oldY] = coord(i - offset);
    grid[newY][newX] = grid[oldY][oldX];
  }

  return grid;
};
```

