Strictly by the definition, I contaminate and reconstruct the tree, all the while adding the keys to a set. 

The latter makes the initial tree building O(n), but the find operation O(1), since we can look the keys up directly from the set.

I'm sure I can make this faster by combining 'contaminate' and 'reconstruct', but It's late now and I'm tired :)

```
class FindElements {

    HashSet<Integer> keys;

    public FindElements(TreeNode root) {
        keys = new HashSet<Integer>();
        contaminate(root);
        root.val = 0;
        reconstruct(root);
    }

    public boolean find(int target) {
       return keys.contains(target);
    }

    private void contaminate(TreeNode root) {
        if(root == null) {
            return;
        }

        root.val = -1;
        contaminate(root.left);
        contaminate(root.right);
    }

    public void reconstruct(TreeNode root) {
        if(root == null) {
            return;
        }

        keys.add(root.val);

        if(root.left != null) {
            root.left.val = 2*root.val + 1;

        }

        if(root.right != null) {
            root.right.val = 2*root.val + 2;
        }

        reconstruct(root.left);
        reconstruct(root.right);
    }
}

```

